Building Pipelines and Testing Models¶

I wrote a function to construct pre-processing pipelines for our features. Below I use it to process features and then run a randomized search to tune hyperparameters on a model. After we've experimentally found adequate values for the hyperparameters, we can then use this pre-processing pipeline inside larger pipelines, like for instance if we wanted to build a stacking model (which is exactly what I'm getting around to)

In [2]:
pipe = utils.build_pre_pipe()
pipe.show(detailed=True)

We can now perform this sequence of transformations on the features simply by invoking the DAG object's fit_transform method (or just transform depending on context).

If you know how to read an ROC curve you'll immediately notice that the model is underfit. That's to be expected as this is a very tough dataset and naive Bayes is a simple model.

Anyhow. Now that we identified a good value for 'var_smoothing' we can build a larger pipeline that contains the entire pre-processing pipeline as a single node.

In [9]:
nb_clf = (
    DAGBuilder()

    .add_step(
        "preprocess_nb",
        utils.build_pre_pipe()
    )

    .add_step(
        "NaiveBayes",
        GaussianNB(var_smoothing=0.0003511191734215131),  # hyperparameter value found experimentally
        deps=["preprocess_nb"]
    )
).make_dag()

In [22]:
start = 1  # the degree to start the search
stop = 6  # the degree to stop the search
grid_collection = []

for degree in range(start, stop + 1):

    title = f'Logistic Regression, polynomial degree: {degree}'
    kwargs = {
        "cmap": "viridis",
        "group_names": ["True Negatives","False Positives","False Negatives","True Positives"],
        "title": title
    }

    param_grid = {
        "solver": ["newton-cholesky"],
        "class_weight": ["balanced"],
        "C": [1e-5, 1e-1, 1e1, 5e1],
        "n_jobs": [-1]
    }
    gs_logr = GridSearchCV(
        estimator=LogisticRegression(),
        param_grid=param_grid,
        cv=2,
        verbose=1,
        scoring='precision'
    )

    preproc = utils.build_pre_pipe(features, degree=degree, polynomial_features=polynomial_features)
    X_train_temp = preproc.fit_transform(X_train).values
    X_val_temp = preproc.transform(X_val).values

    gs_logr.fit(X_train_temp, y_train)
    train_pred = gs_logr.predict(X_train_temp)
    predictions = gs_logr.predict(X_val_temp)

    grid_collection.append(gs_logr)


    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(5, 8))

    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(train_pred, y_train)
    fprts, tprts, _ = roc_curve(predictions, y_val)
    utils.plot_roc(ax1, fpr,tpr,fprts,tprts,f'Logistic Regression Classifier (degree={degree})')

    cm = confusion_matrix(y_val, predictions)
    utils.make_confusion_matrix(cm, ax2, **kwargs)
    fig.tight_layout()

XGBoost¶

Using XGBoost turns out to be a bit more involved than what we've seen so far (GaussianNaiveBayes and LogisticRegression). It is not implemented in sklearn but comes from a different specialized software package. And although it is compatible with sklearn in the sense that it has the same methods that you would expect from the sklearn model APIs (e.g. fit, fit_predict, etc), it's method signatures may differ.

In this case, in order to use early-stopping to help mitigate overfitting, we need to pass an evaluation set as a model parameter

xgb_clf.fit(X_train, y_train, eval_set=[(X_val, y_val)])

The DAG package we are using to create the pipelines is not sophisticated enough to infer what we mean if we call ensemble_model.fit(X, y, eval_set). It can only handle a call with parameters (X, y).

To deal with this I wrote a wrapper class for XGBClassifier named XGBC

In [10]:
#  Experimentally determined params
xgb_params = {'subsample': 0.9,
          'scale_pos_weight': 10,
          'reg_lambda': 0,
          'reg_alpha': 100,
          'n_estimators': 1000,
          'min_child_weight': 5,
          'max_depth': 3,
          'learning_rate': 0.1,
          'gamma': 0.3,
          'eval_metric': 'logloss',
          'early_stopping_rounds': 30,
          'colsample_bytree': 0.7,
          'n_jobs': -1}

xgb_clf = (
    DAGBuilder()

    .add_step(
        "preproc_xgb",
        utils.build_pre_pipe(features, polynomial_features=polynomial_features, degree=3)
    )

    .add_step(
        "XGBoost",
        XGBC(random_state=101, test_size=0.25, **xgb_params),
        deps=["preproc_xgb"]
    )
).make_dag()

    utils.plot_roc(ax1, fpr,tpr,fprts,tprts,f'Simple Voting Classifier ({vote_type} vote)')

    cm = confusion_matrix(y_val, predictions)
    utils.make_confusion_matrix(cm, ax2, **kwargs)
    fig.tight_layout()

Stacking¶

The skdag package has a stacking API. Unfortunately, from what I can tell by briefly inspecting the skdag code myself, the stacking API doesn't implement any kind of system that would ensure that the downstream estimators are training on data that wasn't produced from fitted predictions on the previous layer (we want either data that hasn't been touched or out-of-fold (OOF) predictions). I could be completely wrong about that. But first I just wanted to create a compound model that implements a blender rather than a voting classifier.

from sklearn.metrics import precision_score

# we predicted probabilities this time, so we need to convert those into binary predictions using some threshold
# we can then modulate the threshold to optimize precision (or whichever metric we desire)
thresholds = np.arange(0.01, 0.7, 0.01)
precision_array = np.zeros(thresholds.shape)
for i in range(len(thresholds)):
    precision_array[i] = precision_score(y_val, predictions[:, 1] > thresholds[i])
threshold = thresholds[np.argmax(precision_array)]

kwargs = {
    "cmap": "magma",
    "group_names": ["True Negatives","False Positives","False Negatives","True Positives"],
    "title": f'Simple Blender optimized for precision (threshold:{threshold: .2f})'
}

fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(5, 8))
fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(train_pred[:, 1] > threshold, y_train)
fprts, tprts, _ = roc_curve(predictions[:, 1] > threshold, y_val)
utils.plot_roc(ax1, fpr,tpr,fprts,tprts,f'Simple Blender')
cm = confusion_matrix(y_val, predictions[:, 1] > threshold)
utils.make_confusion_matrix(cm, ax2, **kwargs)
fig.tight_layout()

To train a multi-layer ensemble, one strategy we can use is called Out Of Fold (OOF) training. We'll split the training set into K folds. Then for each fold k we'll train the layer on the training set. Once the layer is trained, we use the kth test set to make predictions, which we match up with their appropriate labels.

In [3]:
layer_1 = pickle.load(open("models/layer_1.pkl", "rb"))
df_train = pickle.load(open("archive/df_train.pkl", "rb"))

num_observations = len(df_train)
num_layer1_models = 3
X_layer_2 = np.zeros(shape=(num_observations, num_layer1_models))  # pre-allocating space for the next layer's features
y_layer_2 = np.zeros(num_observations)  # pre-allocating for the next layer's labels

index = 0  # keeps track of where we should insert data into the pre-allocated arrays
stratified_k_fold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=3)
for train_index, test_index in stratified_k_fold.split(df_train.drop(target_var, axis=1), df_train[target_var]):
    X_tr = df_train.iloc[train_index, :-1]
    X_tst = df_train.iloc[test_index, :-1]
    y_tr = df_train[target_var].iloc[train_index]
    y_tst = df_train[target_var].iloc[test_index]

    # train the models for this fold
    layer_1.fit(X_tr, y_tr)

    # make predictions for the testing portion (note this is not the test set proper!)
    predictions = layer_1.predict_proba(X_tst)

    # insert data into pre-allocated arrays
    size = len(X_tst)
    print(f'size: {size}')
    X_layer_2[index : index + size] = predictions
    y_layer_2[index : index + size] = y_tst

    # increment index
    index = index + size
